node.title: James Pattinson fined, suspended for dangerous throw
node.description: James Pattinson has been fined his entire match fee for striking Daniel Hughes on the foot with a needless throw during their Sheffield Shield clash at the MCG.

node.title: 'She's nothing like me': Lady Gaga responds to rumours she stayed in character for 18 months for House of Gucci
node.description: Lady Gaga admits she spent nine months in character for her role as Patrizia Reggiani in a film exploring the 1995 murder-for-hire of the heir to Gucci fashion dynasty.

node.title: Your next new car will probably be electric. Here’s what brand it could be
node.description: The federal government says it will not force Australians out of the car they want to drive, but the choice may have already been taken away from them. Here are the car brands that are making the permanent switch to electric.

node.title: The terrifying science behind the crowd crush: This is the moment a group turns deadly
node.description: After the Astroworld disaster that claimed eight lives, investigators and organisers are scrambling to get to the bottom of what caused the deadly crowd crush. The science behind it is frighteningly simple.

node.title: Electric vehicle factory plan collapses and with it the promise of 500 Victorian jobs
node.description: SEA Electric tells the Victorian government it won't be building an EV factory, which was announced with great fanfare by Premier Daniel Andrews in 2018.

node.title: Traffic worker killed in hit-and-run crash remembered as 'hardworking family man' as hunt continues for driver
node.description: A man killed in a hit-and-run crash in Melbourne's south-east is remembered as a loving father of four, as police say they are on track to find the driver.

node.title: 'Partners for life': Malala Yousafzai marries cricket official in the UK
node.description: The world's youngest Nobel Peace Prize laureate Malala Yousafzai, who captured the world's attention after a Taliban attempt on her life, has announced her marriage in the UK.

node.title: We fact checked Alexander Downer on private jet emissions for Glasgow. Here's what we found
node.description: As world leaders and delegates flew into Glasgow for the COP26 climate change summit, former foreign minister Alexander Downer claimed their private jets would generate more emissions in 24 hours than Scotland does in a year. Is that correct? RMIT ABC Fact Check investigates.

node.title: Police say a simple knock helped find NSW's most wanted man
node.description: Mostafa Baluch had evaded authorities for several weeks — in the end, police say they used something very simple to locate the alleged drug smuggler.

node.title: 'Great day' for police as alleged drug smuggler Mostafa Baluch arrested after weeks on the run
node.description: Officers say they found alleged drug smuggler Mostafa Baluch in the back of a truck in Queensland after a costly search spanning four states and several weeks ended in a "great day" for police.

node.title: The World Needs to Quit Oil and Gas. Africa Has an Idea: Rich Countries First.
node.description: As negotiators at the Glasgow climate talks try to agree on greenhouse gas cuts, African leaders say poorer countries can’t be expected to remake their systems as quickly as wealthy ones.

node.title: ‘Free Joe Biden’: Sean Maloney on How Democrats Can Get Back on Track
node.description: In an interview, the leader of the House Democrats’ campaign arm acknowledged the major challenges facing the party but defended its agenda and its continued focus on Donald Trump.

node.title: Rep. Paul Gosar tweet of animation of attacks on AOC, Biden draws fire
node.description: The tweet drew a warning label from Twitter and was widely decried. The firebrand Arizona Republican is a staunch backer of former President Trump.

node.title: How to Do a Voice-Over
node.description: Don’t be afraid to improvise. Avoid saying one line at a time.

node.title: How I Found Comfort in Volunteer Firefighting
node.description: Facing a world on fire turns out to be a great way not to contemplate one’s own misfortunes.

node.title: What Do I Owe My Difficult Mother-in-Law?
node.description: The magazine’s Ethicist columnist and why offering regular help creates sometimes unwelcome obligations of its own — and more.

node.title: The 1619 Project and the Long Battle Over U.S. History
node.description: Fights over how we tell our national story go back more than a century — and have a great deal to teach us about our current divisions.

node.title: Your Walls Don’t Have to Be Boring
node.description: Faced with a blank wall, most of us think paint or wallpaper. But there are more interesting possibilities to consider.

node.title: Scholars Cringe at the Term ‘Dark Ages.’ Dan Jones Explains Why.
node.description: Jones’s book “Powers and Thrones” is a comprehensive history of the Middle Ages that links the medieval era’s genuine achievements to modern times.

node.title: Lily King Tries Her Hand at Something New: Short Stories
node.description: In “Five Tuesdays in Winter,” the longtime novelist strings together a series of small worlds that form their own solar system.

node.title: 4 New Y.A. Fantasy Novels Full of Dark, Enchanting Twists
node.description: These fantasy novels — “Year of the Reaper,” by Makiia Lucier; “Beasts of Prey,” by Ayana Gray; “Skin of the Sea,” by Natasha Bowen; and “Gilded,” by Marissa Meyer — will transport you to magical worlds.

node.title: A New Novel by Louise Erdrich Haunted by Covid and George Floyd’s Death
node.description: Set in Minneapolis mostly during 2020, “The Sentence,” by the Pulitzer Prize-winning novelist, is a ghost story about America’s current traumas that also evokes those of our collective past.

node.title: Women Seeking Intimacy Through Food, Mathematics and Rhythm
node.description: From a New York au pair to a kathak dancer in India to an aspiring mathematician in Oslo, the heroines of three debut novels seek solace in vocation.
